    "Stern received his <em>abitur</em> in 1921 in Munich, Germany where he spent his formative years.": [],
    "From 1922-1929, he studied art history in Heidelberg, Leipzig, and Munich under <a href=\"/wolfflinh\">Heinrich W\u00f6lfflin</a>, <a href=\"/pinderw\">Wilhelm Pinder</a>, and <a href=\"/hauttmannm\">Max Hauttmann</a>.": [],
    "He completed his dissertation <em>M\u00fcnchner Barockplastik von 1660-1720</em> (Munich Baroque Sculpture from 1660-1720) in 1929 working under the direction of <a href=\"/pinderw\">Wilhelm Pinder</a>.": [],
    "He eventually published this work in 1932 in <em>M\u00fcnchner</em>.": [],
    "From 1930-1931, Stern was a scientific assistant at the Residenzmuseum in Munich, which has numerous royal collections and formerly housed the Wittelsbach monarchs of Bavaria.": [],
    "He worked under Freidrich Hofmann (1813-1888), who was the director of the museum.": [
